{
  "NPV measures:": "",
  "The net value created or destroyed by an investment in today's dollars": "",
  "Total revenue of a project in most scenarios involving value": "",
  "Total costs of a project regardless of prevailing conditions": "",
  "Future revenue only regardless of prevailing conditions": "",
  "NPV calculates the difference between the present value of all future cash inflows and the initial investment, telling you whether the project creates or destroys value in today's dollars.": "",
  "If an investment's NPV is positive, the investor should:": "",
  "Renegotiate the terms when considering all": "",
  "Accept the project because it earns more than the required return": "",
  "Reject the project when considering all relevant positive": "",
  "Wait for more data within the broader context of positive": "",
  "A positive NPV means the project's returns exceed the required rate of return (discount rate), creating value for the investor. The NPV decision rule says to accept all positive-NPV projects.": "",
  "If an investment's NPV is negative, the investor should:": "",
  "Accept it if the payback period is short": "",
  "Accept it anyway since all investments have risk": "",
  "Double the investment to make up for losses": "",
  "Reject the project because it does not meet the required return": "",
  "A negative NPV indicates the investment's returns fall short of the required rate of return, meaning it destroys value. Rational investors should reject negative-NPV projects.": "",
  "A $50,000 investment generates $15,000 per year for 5 years. At a 10% discount rate, the Year 1 present value is:": "",
  "$15,000": "",
  "$13,636": "",
  "$12,000": "",
  "$14,000": "",
  "Year 1 PV = $15,000 / (1.10)^1 = $15,000 / 1.10 = $13,636.36. Each future cash flow must be discounted back to the present by dividing by (1 + r)^n.": "",
  "For the same investment, the Year 2 present value of $15,000 at 10% is:": "",
  "$13,000": "",
  "$11,000": "",
  "$12,397": "",
  "Year 2 PV = $15,000 / (1.10)^2 = $15,000 / 1.21 = $12,396.69, approximately $12,397. Each successive year's cash flow is discounted more heavily.": "",
  "If the discount rate increases from 10% to 15%, the NPV of a project will:": "",
  "Double when considering all relevant rate factors": "",
  "Increase regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "Decrease because future cash flows are discounted more heavily": "",
  "Stay the same, based on conventional assumptions about": "",
  "A higher discount rate reduces the present value of each future cash flow, which lowers the total NPV. This inverse relationship between discount rate and NPV is fundamental to understanding rate sensitivity.": "",
  "NPV is calculated as:": "",
  "Average annual profit times the number of years": "",
  "Sum of all discounted future cash flows minus the initial investment": "",
  "Initial investment divided by annual cash flow": "",
  "Total cash inflows minus total cash outflows without discounting": "",
  "NPV = Sum of [Cash Flow_t / (1+r)^t] for each period minus the initial investment. Each future cash flow is discounted back to its present value before being summed.": "",
